10.body: Quarto allows you to combine text, code, and results in one file. Click File > New File > Quarto Document... Title it "Lab 2" and put your name as the Author. Click Create . Look at the file. You will see: YAML Header: The stuff between the --- lines (Title, Author, Format). Code Chunks: The gray boxes starting with ```{r}. Markdown: The plain white areas for your written analysis.

11.body: To turn your code into a report: Click the Render button (blue arrow icon) at the top of the editor. RStudio will save the file and pop up a beautiful HTML window. **Lab Task 2:** Inside your Quarto document, create a new code chunk and type `2 + 2`. Render the document and verify that the number `4` appears in the final report. Screenshot your rendered HTML for submission.

2.title: Learning Objectives

3.body: To perform data science at DCC, we use two primary tools. Think of R as the "engine" of a car and RStudio as the "dashboard." You need the engine to go, but you need the dashboard to steer and see where you are going. If you are using a DCC Chromebook or a computer where you cannot install software, please contact the instructor about using **Posit Cloud** (the web-based version of RStudio).
3.breadcrumbs: Lab 1: R and RStudio Installation » Introduction
3.title: Introduction

4.body: You must install R before you install RStudio. Go to the CRAN (Comprehensive R Archive Network) website. Select the download link for your operating system: Download R for Windows -> Click "base" -> Click "Download R 4.x.x for Windows." Download R for (macOS) -> Download the .pkg file that matches your chip (Apple silicon M1/M2 or Intel). Run the downloaded installer and keep all default settings by clicking "Next" or "Continue."

5.body: RStudio is the interface where you will write your code and view your data visualizations. Visit the Posit Download Page . Scroll down to "2: Install RStudio" and click the button for your operating system. Run the installer. Like R, it is best to keep all default settings.

8.body: Create an RStudio Project to organize your work. Understand the structure of a Quarto (.qmd) document. "Render" a document into a professional HTML report.
8.breadcrumbs: Lab 2: RStudio Projects and Quarto » Learning Objectives
8.title: Learning Objectives

9.body: In Data Science, organization is everything. An RStudio Project keeps your code, data, and images in one "folder" so R always knows where to look. Open RStudio. Click File > New Project... Select New Directory > New Project . Name your directory MAT186_Labs and save it to your Desktop or Documents. **Why use Projects?** It sets the "Working Directory" automatically. You'll never have to type long file paths like `C:/Users/Documents/Data...` again!
